Day 2: Props & Component Reusability
1. What are Props?

Props (Properties) are used to pass data from a parent component to a child component.

Think of props as function parameters.

Example
Welcome.jsx
function Welcome(props) {
    return (
        <h2>Welcome {props.name}</h2>
    );
}

export default Welcome;
App.jsx
import Welcome from './components/Welcome';

function App() {
    return (
        <div>
            <Welcome name="Priyadharshini" />
        </div>
    );
}

export default App;
Output
Welcome Priyadharshini
2. Destructuring Props (Recommended)

Instead of:

function Welcome(props) {
    return (
        <h2>{props.name}</h2>
    );
}

Use:

function Welcome({ name }) {
    return (
        <h2>Welcome {name}</h2>
    );
}

export default Welcome;

This is the preferred React style.

3. Functional Components

You've already created functional components.

Example:

function Header() {
    return (
        <h1>My Portfolio</h1>
    );
}

export default Header;

Functional Components:

Easier to write
Use Hooks
Most commonly used in modern React
4. Component Reusability

Suppose you want to display multiple employees.

Employee.jsx
function Employee({ name, role }) {
    return (
        <div>
            <h3>{name}</h3>
            <p>{role}</p>
        </div>
    );
}

export default Employee;
App.jsx
import Employee from './components/Employee';

function App() {
    return (
        <div>
            <Employee
                name="Priyadharshini"
                role="Java Developer"
            />

            <Employee
                name="Arun"
                role="React Developer"
            />

            <Employee
                name="Kumar"
                role="Full Stack Developer"
            />
        </div>
    );
}

export default App;
Output
Priyadharshini
Java Developer

Arun
React Developer

Kumar
Full Stack Developer

Notice:

Same component used 3 times
Different data passed through props

This is called Component Reusability.


Interview Questions
What are Props?

Props are used to pass data from a parent component to a child component.

Are Props Mutable?

No. Props are read-only (immutable).

Difference Between Props and State?
Props	State
Passed from parent	Managed inside component
Read-only	Can be changed
Used for communication	Used for dynamic data
What is Component Reusability?

Using the same component multiple times with different data by passing props.
